sentences.text: MINPRAN , a new robust operator , nds good ts in data sets where more than 50 % of the points are outliers .
Unlike other techniques that handle large outlier percentages , MINPRAN does not rely on a known error bound for the good data .
Instead it assumes that the bad data are randomly -LRB- uniformly -RRB- distributed within the dynamic range of the sensor .
Based on this , MINPRAN uses random sampling to search for the t and the number of inliers to the t that are least likely to have occurred randomly .
It runs in time O -LRB- N 2 + SN log N -RRB- , where S is the number of random samples and N is the number of data points .

We demonstrate analytically that MINPRAN distinguishes good ts from ts to random data , and that MINPRAN nds accurate ts and nearly the correct number of inliers , regardless of the percentage of true inliers .
MINPRAN 's properties are connrmed experimentally on synthetic data and compare favorably to least median of squares .
Related work applies MINPRAN to complex range and intensity data 23 -RSB- .

Predicate-are.label: are
Predicate-are.description: The predicate 'are' indicates a relationship between the subject and object in which the subject possesses or consists of the qualities described by the object. It can be used to describe various types of equivalence, similarity, or classification.

Predicate-handles.label: handles
Predicate-handles.description: The predicate 'handles' indicates a relationship where the subject has control or management over the object. It suggests that the subject is responsible for dealing with, managing, or coping with the situation described by the object.

Predicate-uses.label: uses
Predicate-uses.description: The predicate 'uses' indicates a relationship where the subject entity employs or utilizes the object concept, method, technique, or tool to achieve a specific purpose or goal.

Predicate-searches_for.label: searches for
Predicate-searches_for.description: The predicate 'searches for' indicates that the subject (an entity or individual) actively seeks out and attempts to find or locate the object. This connection implies a sense of inquiry, investigation, or pursuit, suggesting that the subject has some level of interest or motivation in discovering the object.

Predicate-distinguishes.label: distinguishes
Predicate-distinguishes.description: The predicate 'distinguishes' connects a subject (e.g., MINPRAN) with an object that represents a distinction or separation, indicating that the subject has the ability to differentiate between two or more entities, concepts, or categories. In general, it implies a process of identifying and separating one thing from another based on specific characteristics, features, or criteria.

Predicate-nds.label: nds
Predicate-nds.description: The predicate 'nds' indicates a relationship where the subject has some degree of similarity or approximation to the object. The connection between the subject and object suggests that there may be a partial match, an estimate, or a rough equivalence.

Predicate-have.label: have
Predicate-have.description: The predicate 'have' indicates a relationship of possession or ownership between the subject and object. It suggests that the subject has control over, responsibility for, or holds something (physical or abstract) as its own.

Predicate-compare_favorably_to.label: compare favorably to
Predicate-compare_favorably_to.description: The predicate 'compare favorably to' indicates a relationship where the subject and object are being evaluated against each other. The comparison suggests that the subject has similar or better qualities, characteristics, or attributes compared to those of the object.

Predicate-applies.label: applies
Predicate-applies.description: The predicate 'applies' indicates a relationship where the subject (a concept or idea) has relevance, pertinence, or effectiveness to the object (another concept, method, or approach). It suggests that the subject can be used, employed, or utilized for achieving a specific goal or solving a particular problem.

Predicate-to.label: to
Predicate-to.description: The predicate 'to' indicates a relationship of correspondence or equivalence between two entities. It suggests that the subject and object are connected by sharing similar characteristics, properties, or values.

Predicate-assumes.label: assumes
Predicate-assumes.description: The predicate 'assumes' indicates that the subject takes something as true or given without necessarily verifying its accuracy. It implies a mental attitude of acceptance and reliance on the object, which can be an idea, concept, data, or situation.

Predicate-finds.label: finds
Predicate-finds.description: The predicate 'finds' indicates that the subject has discovered or identified the object as being true or existing. It implies a sense of discovery, recognition, or verification.

Predicate-are_assumed_to_be_randomly_dis.label: are assumed to be randomly distributed within
Predicate-are_assumed_to_be_randomly_dis.description: The predicate 'are assumed to be randomly distributed within' indicates a relationship where the subject's characteristics or properties are thought to be evenly spread across the object, without any inherent pattern or bias.

skos:broader.label: has a broader term
skos:broader.description: The predicate 'has a broader term' indicates that the subject is related to or encompasses the object as a more general concept. It suggests a hierarchical relationship between the two, where the subject represents a higher-level category and the object represents a lower-level subcategory.
